However when michael our oldest brother and the oldest child of my siblings was young our mom, found an interview where a 14 year old girl  was talking about college and how she was just soaring and excelling. My mom was fascinated by her story,  but was a bit wary of the idea because homeschooling wasn't very common at the time in the early 90s. My mom however went to public schools and did not enjoy her experience at all. Due to bullying, and skipping grades she would sometimes be bored and waiting for the lecture to be over with. So she wanted us to advance at our own pace instead of being rushed or forced. And be able to skip grades if that was what was best for us. Her and dad decided to home school all of us from k-12 and developed their own curriculum which focused on Latin, greek, classic literature, catholic faith and critical thinking. Mom wanted us to have to learn to think for ourselves, to be curious and love learning, and to have strong moral compasses. she signed  us up for every activity possible in our  area- swim team, musical theatre, basketball, gymnastics, Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts, karate, and many more. We all grew up to be a loud, vibrant bunch. We were very well “socialized” and had a lot of friends. Most people didn’t guess we were homeschooled when they met us because of our social and people skills.
  

  To this day, we all count our homeschool experience as one of the greatest tools in our lives and careers. Because of homeschooling, we have had a lot of free time to learn instruments, practice singing and harmonizing, and write songs. Homeschooling gave us the space to be free to be ourselves.
